* `JSON.parse` has return type `any` by design -- the type system cannot
  know what shape an arbitrary JSON string will produce at runtime. This
  means every JSON.parse result is a trust-me assertion, not a verified
  contract. The annotation `const data: User = JSON.parse(...)` is you
  promising the compiler the shape is right -- it cannot check.

* `any` is contagious but silent: once a value is `any`, all downstream
  property accesses, assignments, and call results are also `any`. No
  error is raised even in strict mode. This is distinct from `unknown`,
  which forces an explicit check before use.

* The fix is validation at the system boundary (where external data
  enters your program), not a stronger type annotation. Libraries like
  `zod` or `valibot` parse-and-validate in one step and return a typed
  result only on success.
